Translation based on the Ahtna Athabaskan Dictionary by James Kari (1990: 270): “ten things, lit. possibly 'bare hands'”.
Translation based on the Ahtna Athabaskan Dictionary by James Kari (1990: 255).

10 here is not deztaan but deetaan but I consider this still similar enough. Possibly also a typo? No attestation of deetaan in Kari’s dictionary. This form of 19 is not attested there either (numeral system on p. 634).
Deztaan and xundelaayi seem to be dialectal lexical variants of 10.
Translation based on the Ahtna Athabaskan Dictionary by James Kari (1990: 295): “twenty, lit. 'one man'”
Might contain 10 historically? Tseles is ‘1’ according to kari (1990: 263).
Delaay as in xundelaayi ‘10’? And na- looks like ‘2’.
